<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&gt; Should our police be prophets? How should they arrive before<br>
any crime is comitted?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Se the movie &quot;the Minority Report&quot; for a cinematic use of precognitives in crime prevention.<br>
Short of that, after we disarm the people so that nobody can defend themselves, we either accept that a lot people will die because they can't defend themselves and the State can't/won't do it for them, or we must brainwash everybody from youth to prevent hostile actions.<br>
 It's obvious that we can't just outlaw the use of force in an unjust manner (a crime), so we must enumerate, outlaw, and enforce laws against the various specific things which can be used in a crime.<br>
 Rather than going down the line to include everything from guns to pointed sticks to raising your arm as if to strike a blow, we should find it easier to alter the brain and human behavior to prevent these hostile urges from being acted upon.<br>
Gun crime statistics in nations which have completely outlawed posession of firearms showing that simply outlawing them won't prevent outlaws from getting them, we should immediately begin a Manhattan Project style crash program to find the best techniques for mass population brainwashing.<br>
We should rewrite the Constitution and the Declaration of independence to say that people don't have any rights in and of themselves, unless the State is willing/able to provide for them. If the State isn't there, then it is everybody's fate to die if needed at the hands of a barbarian who slipped through the brainwashing, because it's too dangerous to let the poor little sheeple have the ability to protect themselves.<br>
<br>
Either that, or we continue to allow and actually encourage people to buy and train in the use of such things as guns. Let people act as if they really do have rights apart from what/when the government is willing/able to give them, and that they have the right to the ability to protect these rights themselves.<br>
 It would seem to be easier &amp; cheaper than the alternatives, and since the present thing being urged is unilateral disarmament of the victims of crimes, it strikes me as the moral thing to do -unless we should really consider a woman who's been raped to death as morally superior to one standing with a smoking gun over the corpse of her would-be attacker. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zentrander>Zentrander</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 148<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/13/03 10:01 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=449.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: How to keep the peace?</span><hr size=1> I just would like to point out that repealing an amendment is not unconsitutional.  Our constitution was written to be fluid, and amendments can be undone by other amendments, as long as those other amendments can be legally upheld. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=johnfraz>John Fraz</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_yingyang.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 393<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/27/03 3:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=449.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://lneilsmith.com/tools/littlelogo.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: &quot;repealing an amendment&quot;</span><hr size=1> I wrote (sarcastically about mass bra